As @Dogopotamus noted the average needed to reach 30k (755) is over 200 cases greater than what the current 7 day average is (528). I would add that even if there was a one day spike of 1400 cases, if the other 3 days kept with the 7 day average then 30k cases would not be reached. So it would take a sustained spike to break 30k, which seems unlikely with the recent decline in cases.

Thanks to catches from @tmcgraw and @Dogopotamus, realized I had the incorrect estimation duration. Based on the update timing, it looks like the 29th will be the last set of data available on the 30th. With that in mind, based on current data, the average will need to be 712 for the next 5 days.

Adjustment due to progression/update. As of today morning July 26th, cases are 26,558. For it to cross 30,000 an average of 688 per day would be required. This is looking like roughly the average of the recent days, therefore equally likely to land just below or just above 30,000. Difference is that the curve shape in Orange County FL suggests that the peak is behind us, therefore the days forward I expect confirmed cases lower than, rather than higher than the average. For this I put extra weight at the lower bracket. It will be marginal either way.

Dashboard has it as of 24 July. So up to 6 days worth of data could be added by end of day July 30. Would require 635 positives per day. This is a bit above the recent average. However, looks to be overdue for a positive case spike (caused by data dump or bulk return of tests) so that could push it over 30k.

Current case number is 26.559 and there are 5 days left. This means that the 30000 bracket needs 688 cases a day. Most case numbers for the recent weeks posted in the comments look smaller. But data might get delayed on the weekend, such that we see a lot more cases on monday?

Cases in Florida have grown in the last month or so, however the rate of growth in reported cases seems to be stabilizing a bit in the last few days, but only for now. Data is trending towards close to 28-29 thousand at the end of the month and a slight increase in the rate of growth will put the numbers over 30k by the end of the month. Case growth in other states can also tie up testing resources, slowing confirmation of cases everywhere. Also, unfortunately the data is being routed through a political faction instead of the CDC, allowing for the numbers to be skewed lower. This all does not include reported probable or likely cases, which in any larger outbreak tends to be much higher than the number of identified cases.

Revising this after the recent couple of days explosion in confirmed incidents in Orange County FL. Low bookend: 500 new per day x 17 days remaining in July = 8.500 + 18.639 = 27.139 total cases on 30th July. High bookend: 900 new per day x 17 days = 15.300 + 18.639 = 33.939 total by 30th July. The bracket split is at 30.000 cases so my bookends are unevenly distributed on each side, with more of my distribution falling in the high bracket. I am at the beach right now so not in the mood to apply standard deviation calcs (also I believe the exponential curve would be slightly more complicated than normal distribution) so I will approximate the probabilities by saying 60% of my distribution is above the 30.000 limit.

As of today July 14th the last two days have seen an explosion of confirmed infections which makes me revise my estimate upwards to: Low bookend: 500 new per day x 17 days = 8.500 + 18639 = 27.139 at 30 July. High bookend: 900 new per day x 17 days = 15.300 + 18.639 = 33.939 at 30 July. The bracket in the question splits at 30.000, leaving more to the high side than to the low side. Hence I assign 60% to the >30.000 bracket.

Average daily cases for the past 7 days is ~600. ~500 excluding today (1371 new cases). There are 18k total cases. A reasonable lower bound would be 500*18+18000 = 27k. For total cases to be <25k, daily cases would have to be <400 for the next 18 days. For total cases to be >30k, daily cases would have to be >666 for the next 18 days. Given the current daily case average and the fact that Florida is continuing to open (including Disney World), this is entirely possible. However, daily totals have only exceeded 666 four times so far.
